Okay.
This is Thursday, a sunny Thursday, March 15 at 1205 Winding Road.
And I have the pleasure and honor of chatting with Dr. Donald.
Don Lewis.
Don, Don Lewis, L-E-W-I-S.
Don, to begin with, introduce yourself to anyone who might hear this tape or read the transcription.
Describe, give us a biographical sketch before you got to A&M.
Where'd you grow up?
Family, go to high school, college, and so forth.
Well, I grew up in Rotan, Texas.
It's a small community out in West Texas about 60 miles northwest of Abilene.
The

high school was the Roten yellow hammers that's somewhat unique and that and someone and I'm it might have been you that told me the origin of the of the someone told me the origin of that but I've never seen a yellow hammer frankly oh which a bird yes oh yes yes yes I know it's a bird but I I didn't see any out there anyway um
I was one of those individuals that started at five and graduated a year earlier.
What did mom and dad do?
Dad worked at the National Gypsum Company.
Rotan happens to be, at that time, it was probably the world's largest store of gypsum.
There's an extremely large store of gypsum in that area.
So that part of the country, or at least that small community, had the fame of being a large gypsum place and near a very large pool of oil.
A lot of people in the small town of Snyder got very wealthy almost overnight.
We unfortunately weren't one of those.
So I went to high school at Rotan and graduated in 1953.
Then I was actually offered a music scholarship to two places, to Tarleton and to actually the University of Texas.
And I guess that came from the fact that I was
in the band and I had gone to all state band and that sort of thing, which was smart.
Music has always been an avocation of mine and I really enjoyed playing and have always enjoyed music.
But my first year I went to Tarleton and then from there I went to the University of Texas.

and I didn't feel that I had time at least at the University of Texas the symphony and the various music activities demanded a lot of time which I didn't feel that I had because my intention was to go to medical school and at that time and perhaps less so

now than it was then getting into medical school was very very competitive and so I had to maintain you know a pretty good grade point average in order to be in order for it to be a realistic goal well I did go on through the paces and I had many odd jobs one odd job involved
I played in a small combo.
We used to sing and play at various fraternities and made, you know, I have gigs on the weekends.
What did you play?
Trombone.
And I sang, I sang, we, we, the group that were doing this weren't using any music.
We would listen to a record and try to duplicate it as best we could to duplicate the sound that they were having and I'm not sure
Whether we did or didn't, but anyway, we had a lot of fun doing that.
In fact, too much fun one semester.
So I stopped doing that and took a job.
Actually, I took a job at the Austin State Hospital, which was a real good job and sort of in tune with what my career goals were at that time.
It gave me room, board, and laundry.
and $175 a month, which was a lot of money at that time.
So I worked there for a while, and then I had an opportunity to work in another, to go to another place.
I had state funding and that sort of thing, and even had what,
I believe it was called Teacher's Retirement, but I wasn't there long enough.
I was there for about a year and a half.
And went to work for a place called Brown Schools, which was a school for emotionally disturbed kiddos.
And not that that was necessarily my career interest, but I thought it would be an interesting job because I did kind of like to work with youth anyway.
And it was there that I met Carol, Carol, my wife.

and she was interested in becoming a, ultimately she became a counselor, but she was going to Texas Woman's University and I was still at the University of Texas with the objective of going to medical school at the end of my, after graduation.

and so we worked, Carol and I worked together as counselors and among other counselors at the Brown School and then she went back to TWU and I was still at the University of Texas and finally I finished and at that time you know we were all subject to draft if we weren't in school and so
I had applied to medical school and I didn't get in the first time.
So I wondered what I was gonna do.
And then the draft board was breathing down my neck saying that, you know, you need to either be in school or we need to, you know.
So I signed up to go into the army and I signed up as a medical laboratory specialist.
Now I was one of the few
In those days, of course, it's common these days for enlisted people to have degrees and not be commissioned, but it was very unusual during those days.
So I went in as a non-commissioned person, and during a basic training,

they did these various tests and it just so happened that I had been a ham radio operator when I was in high school and I knew Morse code very well and I'd enlisted to be a medical laboratory specialist but when they found that I was proficient in Morse code they really tried to push me to go into into the signal core in fact they tried to push me to go into

uh all the the secret service and that sort of thing you know that they want you to well I convinced them that I didn't want to do that and so I did go and take medical training and then during this time Carol and I were still communicating and I was going to be an instructor there at Sam Houston Fort Sam Houston
And because the commanding officer wanted me to be, I was one of the few people that had a degree.
Well, my major was zoology, but I had a lot of hours in microbiology and a lot of hours in chemistry.
I'm not sure whether this is the sort of thing you want or not, but this is just a stream of thought.
And I had pretty strong foundations in those areas, so they wanted to keep me there at San Antonio.
And I thought, man, this will be great.
Carol can go ahead and finish up her degree, and I'll be there in San Antonio, and we can... Well, it just so happened that there was an E-5, a sergeant.
I was a private E-2 at that time.
And...
He wanted to go to Germany because his wife was from Germany and I wanted to stay there because my fiance was in Texas and I thought this was going to be ideal.
Something happened, the orders got switched and Sergeant, which I wasn't a sergeant, I was private, Sergeant Donald Lewis was going to go to the UCR medical lab

and private I've forgotten what the sergeant's name was now was to stay there for instruction and he didn't have the training he I don't think he had a college I don't think he had any college training and so he really tried to talk to the powers that be that so that he could go to Germany and and and I really tried to talk to the powers to be so that I could stay there but it didn't work out that way so oh that was the biggest crisis of our life

And so we, I went, so we went on, I went on over to Germany, not knowing really what I was, you know, Carol and I were going to be apart for three years and I'm not sure we'd be the same person, you know, afterwards.
So, so we, so I did go on to Germany.
And while there, I met the, I was, I was with, with a great group of people.
One person who really had a lot of influence on my training and on my future career, Ken Dirks, he lives in this community, incidentally.
Spell Dirks.
D-I-R-K-S.
He was a major at that time.
Later on, I found that he became a,

you know after I'd gone and everything he became a major general but he he was also a one of one of the I don't know if this interim or what but he was a dean here at the at the medical school here but he was you know he and his family were great well Carol graduated she she
She took 21 hours a semester and pushed through getting through and so she, to kind of make a long story short, she met me over in Germany and we lived on the economy.
At that time I wasn't eligible for housing on the post so we lived on the economy and we lived off of my salary for what we could, you know, what we could on the economy.
And because we both kind of had an interest in
you know, youth and child, you know, child development and that sort of thing.
Let's see, seems like someone, my commanding officer, not Ken, but my commanding officer asked if we would stay with their kiddos for two weeks while they went on annual leave.
And so we did, and again, to make a long story short, we stayed more in people's houses
doing that than, than anything else.
And we, you know, I stayed, I stayed in, in generals and we stayed in general squatters and, and things like that.
And, and a lot of times before they knew what we were doing, they, they were, you know, what are you, private, what are you walking over here for?
So, um, the, the experience at, and this was in Landstuhl,

spell that L-A-N-D-S-T-H-U-L it was the USAR reference laboratory for Europe and so I mean it was just like a college campus and as far as I know it's still still very much that way it's sort of the army reference laboratory for for Europe so I got some experiences that I I don't believe I could have gotten anywhere else

I was exposed to you know various techniques for cell culture which was kind of new at that time was kind of instrumental in in developing immunofluorescence or fluorescence antibody techniques for that lab at that time and let's see we also there well this was during the this was in 1960 when the

when the reserves were activated, the army reserves were activated, and a number of people were suddenly, their lives were just suddenly turned around, so they suddenly showed up over there in Germany, and they were going to be there for a couple of three, at least a couple of three months, and perhaps longer, because this was the Berlin Wall crisis, the beginning of the Berlin Wall crisis.
And I'm assuming that these experiences are adding to your

uh health care yeah my goal yeah whatever of some sort yeah and please let me know if if this is not what you want because I this again like I say this is just stream of conscious now then you come back about when yeah um I come back in uh 62.
62 I thought that I would go back and and
I was kind of fearful of jumping right back into a medical school program, because I was fairly confident I wouldn't have had much problem getting in, particularly with my background.

And so I decided I'd pursue a degree program, but I decided that it would probably be smarter for me to go to a place where I wouldn't have to work quite as hard for a graduate degree as the University of Texas might be.
did a master's degree at Southwest Texas, which proved to be a very good thing.
I was doing some things that were kind of cutting edge from my Army experience.
I was working with Bacteriophage and Salmonella.
and what that does is at that time I was working with mapping genes with bacteriophage which is really pretty far advanced and the only reason why it wasn't

because I was so clever but it was because I had been exposed to some of that type of material in the in the army so and my my thesis has to do with with the transduction in salmonella and that sort of thing so then after getting that finished I thought well I think I'm ready to so I went on made it made the application for for medical school
I really preferred to stay here in Texas.
And let's see, Texas Tech didn't have a school at that time.
I believe there were two schools, Southwest Texas and Galveston.
And so I applied to those two schools, and I was called for an interview.
And I was called for an interview.
On one of the interviews, I went up to Dallas for the interview.
And our first son had came along at that time.

which and we were still in financial straits we stayed in financial straits for most of most even even for a short short period of time even while I was a faculty member here so Donald our oldest son was born at that time and we were somewhat in debt from our from my school days there in in southwest Texas and so I was coming back from

from Dallas and uh I was gonna I was on my way to the farm, Carol's parents farm in Thorndale and and I stopped at uh I happened to stop here in College Station because that happened to be one route by which I could get to Thorndale and there's a as we mentioned the other day there's a service there was a service station a Sinclair service station where Cafe XL is now and uh
I was just kind of talking.
I just said, you know, I wish, what do they have here on this campus?

And we got to, me and one of the guys was visiting there, and it just so happened that there was a student there that said, you know, I've heard that they've got some assistantships out at the vet school.
Well, veterinary medicine was the furthest thing from my mind.
But I thought, well, you know,
I could get into a holding pattern at least, and maybe we could get out of this financial strait that we're in.
And so I went out and talked to, actually, Leland.
Leland Grumbles.
Leland Grumbles and Charlie Hall, the other Charlie Hall.
And they said, yeah, we'd like for you to consider coming here.
I said, well, I've got a master's degree.
I'm not interested in pursuing.
Well, we'd like for you to come here.
We didn't want you to come here.
We would like for you to pursue a Ph.D. And this is Veterinary Microbiology?
Veterinary Microbiology.
And when is this?
This is 66.
No, no, 64.
Fall of 64?
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
Well, actually summer.
I mean, getting ready for the fall.
Yeah.
Mm-hmm.
So I came on board.
I came and started, you know, as a graduate student.
What did they offer you in terms of compensation and assignments?
Well, I believe the amount was, it seemed like it was about $8,000 or $10,000.
I mean, at that time, and to me, that was a fantastic amount.
And this was for a 12-month task?
Yes, uh-huh.
What were your duties?
Well, primarily to pursue graduate work, but to help in the instruction in microbiology, because I had a pretty strong background, I mean, you know, in microbiology.
Describe your first duties.
Well, we had students
the vet students, because there wasn't a very big graduate program at that time.
So I was to lecture to the vet students and help in the labs.
What course or courses?
Microbiology.
What year for them?
It was their second year.
They were second year students at that time.
Describe the students at that time.
Well,
Let's see, I'm trying to think of some of the students I knew.
I don't know whether you want me to use names or not.
You use names wherever it would help.
Yeah, I don't think I will use names, but there were a couple of three students that had gone to Southwest Texas while I was a graduate student.

and they were in vet school at that time and so they were the students were I think consistently the students the vet students have been certainly cut above the usual undergraduates these were all male all male all male all male yes no no females at that as far as I know there weren't any and no minority no black

none whatsoever okay right and in terms of their background as far as you recall where did they come from were they urban kids or no there was a good mix they were they were no there wasn't a good they were primarily rural they were rural primarily rural the the urban I suspect that most of the kiddos that were urban there were a lot of people that that went that went to
that were planning to go to medical school that came to veterinary school, I think, as a secondary option.
That's the sense that I had from, I mean, a fairly significant number of people that were just wanting to be in some sort of health care.
What kind of orientation or prep or training or anything did they give you before you walked?
Oh, boy, I walked in cold.
walked in cold and I was not a you know I was kind of a I've never been one to be you know comfortable unless I'm singing or something like that lecturing but I soon felt like I was in my element
And what year in vet school were these students?
Second year.
Second year.
I believe they were second.
Yeah, they were second year.
And some of them were pretty challenging.
They would challenge me, but I feel like I was up to the task because I had practical experience in dealing with them.
About what size were the sections you were teaching and the number?
Let's see.
Oh, gee.
It's primarily in the labs.
Okay.
So would this be a dozen or so?
No, no, there were about 40 or 50.
The labs were arranged so that there were two large laboratories and then we kind of put together the media and explained how to interpret the

reactions and you know how to streak plates and how to isolate the organisms and and that sort of thing now were you doing this alone or was there someone else no there was someone else there was uh no as a matter of fact well no there were some other there were some others there were actually um there was a person um i'll use his name jim grimes

He had had experience with the Texas Department of Public Health and a fellow by the name of Gordon Welch who had actually gone to medical school for three years and I never did know why he dropped out but he came back to get a PhD and myself and there was one other person who had graduated about four years earlier
as a veterinarian, and he was coming back to do graduate work.
I think we four were the first, if not the first, among the first of the people that were pursuing, you know, on the Ph.D. type program.
Now, who was the department head and who was directing this activity?
Leland Grumbles was the department head, a fellow by the name of Paul Youngerman.
Y-O-U-N?
No, it's J-U-N-G-E-R.
And I think he might be another source of stories.
Now, he has a lot of stories, some of which are fabrications, I'm sure, because he was a great story spinner.
But Youngerman was in charge of microbiology.
Grumbles was the department head.
Archie Flowers.
was sort of in charge of, had some responsibilities in the lab.
But they primarily turned it over to us because those guys, Jargeman and, really had never worked in a laboratory situation.
And here, I had worked for three years in an army, you know, medical laboratory, reference medical laboratory situation.
And Jim Grimes had worked in the public health department in Austin.
And Jim was about 30, 35 at the time.
I was the youngest one.
I was about 28 or 29, I think.
And Gordon was, he had been a medical student, but he, as I say, I never really knew why he didn't,

didn't finish but he came back and he was he had had some experience the point is that that really we were probably better prepared to to do the laboratory than than some of the people that were supposed to be doing it really did anybody sit down with y'all and give you any guidelines any directions uh on an ad hoc basis and how what were some of their what was some of their advice their guidance well um

Most of the times they would say, and let's see, they would say, don't be too wordy, make it short and succinct and follow these guidelines, follow this, this that we've, they had outlined some materials.
And don't tolerate any cheating.
And if you, well, and if you encounter any problems, let us know.
Describe a tip for you.
Describe a typical work day.
As a graduate student.
At that time.
What time did you get to the campus, and what did you do for how long?
Oh, this was kind of an exciting time for me.
So I would get to work.
I would usually get to work about 7.30 or so, maybe even earlier.
And the first year that I was there, I was taking, I guess, a relatively heavy load.
I was taking biochemistry, radiation biology.
So I would do some studying at first.
But I was so glad to be doing some real, quote,
quote unquote real research, I would review some of the material that I'd gotten.
The medical sciences library was right down the way from where my office was.
So I would spend some time in the medical, and usually there were people there beginning at about 7 o'clock.
And so sometimes I'd go down there and have a chance to look over some materials.
And then I'd go to class, say,
Didn't have too many 8 o'clock classes, so I'd go to class about 9 o'clock.
I had Mac Prescott.
Maybe I shouldn't be using that.
No, no, don't.
No, dude.
Describe Professor Prescott as a graduate instructor.
He was an outstanding individual.
Truly outstanding.
And I bet he took everything seriously.
Very seriously.
You bet.
In fact...
This was a graduate level, a graduate level biochemistry course.
And most, I didn't know that at the time, but most graduate courses, it's just sort of, you automatically make a B or better.
There were lots of people in his class that didn't pass.
I'm not surprised.
He pressed very hard, but he was just a very interesting, well,
It was very structured, but very, I enjoyed his class very much, but I was one of the few that did.
I found him to be easy to converse with outside of class.
In fact, I would often visit with him about one thing or another.
One thing that I was particularly interested in and the problem that I was working on, I hadn't zeroed in on a particular problem, but I was interested in the use of electrophoretic procedures.
